[One must wonder how the arriving 8:30 AM motorized wheelchair rider did not notice the bat when they 1st sat in it.

If you must handle one of these bats, 1st find a refrigerator-quality medium-duty plastic bag, a.k.a. "Gladbag;" turn it inside out; put your hand into the bag and grasp the bat, preferably in a way it cannot bite you; and place the bat and the bag in a small cardboard box you can close. You may want to get vaccinated just in case afterwards. And look around. If there is 1 sick bat, there will be other sick bats about or a nearby bat-roost this bat may have fallen out of. - Mod.MHJ]

******
[2] USA, North Carolina
Date: Mon 8 Jun 2015
Source: WXII12.com [edited]
http://www.wxii12.com/news/25-cats-exposed-to-rabies-in-Rockingham-County/33468944


Rockingham County health officials are warning residents after more than 24 cats were recently exposed to rabies. Animal Control officials picked up a colony of 25 cats on Saturday [6 Jun 2015] from Settle Bridge Road following the exposure. All the cats were euthanized.

The cats were exposed to the virus Thursday [4 Jun 2015] by a kitten that turned aggressive and attacked litter mates, county health officials said. A relative took the kitten to a vet on Friday [5 Jun 2015], and the kitten tested positive for rabies on Saturday [6 Jun 2015].

Health officials ask anyone who may have been around cats in the Settle Bridge Road area since 20 May 2015 to call the Rockingham County health department at 336-342-5163.

