[Feral colony cats should be vaccinated as well as spayed, castrated, and ear clipped. - Mod.MHJ]

******
[3] USA, Georgia
Date: Tue 9 Jun 2015
Source: The Brunswick News [edited]
http://www.thebrunswicknews.com/news/local_news/family-dog-tests-positive-for-rabies-on-st-simons-island/article_847666ba-1e86-5177-9827-00fd970547cc.html


A family dog on St. Simons Island that fought recently with a raccoon tested positive for rabies after being euthanized, prompting the treatment of 2 island residents for the disease, the Glynn County Health Department reports.

It is the 2nd instance this year [2015] of a family pet being exposed to the disease in Glynn County. The 1st pet was a dog exposed to a rabid fox in January 2015 that wreaked havoc in a Glynn County neighborhood, causing 2 people to seek treatment for the potentially deadly disease.

Sally Silbermann, spokeswoman for the Coastal Health District, which includes Glynn County, said animals are tested for rabies only if there is potential human exposure. Animals must be dead for the brain to be tested for rabies.

The dog lived in West Point Plantation on St. Simons Island and was not up to date on rabies vaccinations, Silbermann said in a release about the rabies case. The people are being treated as a precautionary measure, she added.

Raccoons are known to be one of the most common carriers of rabies and are plentiful on the coast, said Erin Doane, assistant environmental health manager for the Glynn County Health Department. "A lot of wild animals that are native to our area -- like raccoons and foxes -- are known carriers of rabies," Doane said. "That's why it is so important to make sure that pets are vaccinated against the virus."

Glynn County is no stranger to rabies. In the past 18 months, there have been at least 6 potentially rabid fox interactions with humans and several other instances with raccoons.

The health department advises residents to get pets vaccinated for the disease. Rabies is spread primarily by infected animals. Symptoms include changes in behavior, biting, aggression, showing no fear of natural enemies, foaming at the mouth and paralysis. Never feed, handle or unintentionally attract wild animals with open garbage cans or by leaving pet food out at night, health officials say. Never adopt wild animals or bring them into your home, and teach children the same thing, health officials advise.

If an animal bites you, seek medical attention immediately and contact Glynn County Animal Control at 554-7500 and the Glynn County Health Department's Environmental Health Division at 279-2940.

[Byline: Michael Hall]

